{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474470"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:21:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.79,0.12,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4712"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33932"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1774"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4034"},{"type":"tags","id":"9689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34302"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nine-week-old girl is brought to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of fever. She is irritable with reduced feeding and fewer wet nappies. She has vomited twice and her parents noted her stool is looser than usual. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 190/min, blood pressure 58/36 mmHg, respiratory rate 40/min, temperature 38.2\u00b0C, and SpO2 95% on room air. She is irritable but warm and well-perfused. There is no increased work of breathing. Heart sounds are dual, chest is clear, and her abdomen is soft. Neurological examination is grossly normal with no features of meningism. ENT examination is unremarkable. A sepsis protocol is started and intravenous access established. Blood samples are collected for baseline laboratory investigations, CRP, venous blood gas analysis and cultures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lumbar puncture","Commence IV antibiotics and fluid bolus","Collect urine and stool for microscopy, culture and sensitivity","Apply oxygen 2 L/min via nasal prongs","Chest X-ray"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of sepsis, including fever, irritability, poor feeding, and haemodynamic instability (tachycardia and hypotension). Early recognition and treatment of sepsis in infants is crucial to prevent morbidity and mortality. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommence IV antibiotics and fluid bolus\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFluid resuscitation with 10-20 mL/kg of isotonic crystalloid and early administration of broad-spectrum antibiotics within 30 minutes of presentation are key interventions in the initial management of sepsis. Ideally, blood cultures should be obtained before starting antibiotics, but this should not delay treatment if there are difficulties in obtaining samples.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is often indicated in febrile infants to rule out meningitis, it should not delay the initiation of antibiotics and fluid resuscitation in a child with signs of sepsis. It can be performed after the child is stabilized.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollecting urine and stool\u003C/strong\u003E samples for microscopy, culture and sensitivity may help identify the source of infection, but this should not delay the initiation of antibiotics and fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe infant\u0027s oxygen saturation is 95% on room air with no increased work of breathing, so \u003Cstrong\u003Eapplying oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is not immediately necessary. Oxygen therapy should be initiated if there are signs of respiratory distress or hypoxemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered as part of the sepsis workup, especially if there are respiratory symptoms. However, it is not the most urgent next step and should not delay the initiation of antibiotics and fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Early recognition and treatment of sepsis in infants is crucial to prevent morbidity and mortality.","Initial management of sepsis in infants includes fluid resuscitation and early administration of broad-spectrum antibiotics."],"references":["1. Sepsis and septic shock from a urinary tract source in children [Internet]. Therapeutic Guidelines. 2019. Available from: https://etg-complete-oxy.netlify.app/antibiotic/c_sepsis_and_septic_shock_from_a_urinary_tract_source_in_adults","2. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Clinical Practice Guidelines : SEPSIS \u2013 assessment and management [Internet]. Rch.org.au. 2017. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/SEPSIS_assessment_and_management/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33932"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12184"}},"stemMedi